However, just because the symptoms will recede does not mean the underlying problem will go away. <span style="background: none repeat scroll 0% 0% gray;">China,</span> put down by the West for two centuries, <span style="background: none repeat scroll 0% 0% gray;">is cognizant of its growing strength</span> and intends to be recognized for it. <span style="background: none repeat scroll 0% 0% gray;">It</span> also <span style="background: none repeat scroll 0% 0% gray;">has territorial disputes</span> with many neighbors besides Taiwan, <span style="background: none repeat scroll 0% 0% gray;">and a perception that the U</span>nited <span style="background: none repeat scroll 0% 0% gray;">S</span>tates <span style="background: none repeat scroll 0% 0% gray;">wants to box it in</span> militarily and politically. <span style="background: none repeat scroll 0% 0% gray;">Similar conditions</span> -- between the established powers of Russia, Britain and France on one side, and a rising Germany on the other -- helped <span style="background: none repeat scroll 0% 0% gray;">produce World War I</span>. Under these circumstances, the trick is for the United States and allies, most notably Japan, to deter China -- while also reassuring Beijing that we are not picking a fight and that we recognize its rightful place at the table of great powers<span style="font-size: 6pt;">. Getting this policy right requires attention, creativity and some new ideas. China's action will at least have been well-timed if it gives Clinton and Hashimoto a strong sense of purpose about reinvigorating the alliance. Unfortunately, most members of the U.S. and Japanese foreign policy establishments would rather use the summit to endorse the status quo. They take it as gospel that the United States must maintain about 45,000 U.S. troops in Japan and 100,000 in Asia because otherwise Japan and the rest of the region might slip into angst and insecurity. Clinton's own Pentagon officials recently reaffirmed this conventional wisdom with a major strategic review. But </span>there are risks to sticking with the status quo. <span style="background: none repeat scroll 0% 0% gray;">Tension in the U.S.-Japan alliance, revealed</span> so starkly <span style="background: none repeat scroll 0% 0% gray;">on Okinawa</span> last fall after U.S. servicemen raped a 12-year-old Japanese schoolgirl, <span style="background: none repeat scroll 0% 0% gray;">has been developing</span> ever since the end of the Cold War and could easily worsen. Japanese remain pro-American and in favor of the bilateral security relationship. But substantial and growing majorities believe that U.S. bases and military personnel in their country, essentially still at Cold War levels, should be reduced<span style="font-size: 6pt;">. True, the Japanese-American alliance weathered tough times in the past, surviving the Vietnam War and other major challenges. But in those days, the nearby Soviet threat helped the allies to say they were sorry and make up. Moreover, </span>past crises often led to changes in the way the alliance worked -- and this one should too. At this point, <span style="background: none repeat scroll 0% 0% gray;">reinvigorating the alliance could best be accomplished by</span> changing the configuration of U.S. forces in Japan, including <span style="background: none repeat scroll 0% 0% gray;">a reduction in</span> the number of <span style="background: none repeat scroll 0% 0% gray;">Marine combat units on Okinawa</span><span style="font-size: 6pt;">, while asking Japan to play a more forceful role in handling the fundamental future tasks of the alliance. The United States and Japan should distinguish between their vital interests and their important yet less-than-vital interests in Asia. </span>Defense of the open oceans, sea lanes and existing U.S. allies -- Japan, South Korea, Australia, New Zealand, the Philippines and Thailand -- are the chief causes worth fighting for. The United States and Japan should also be prepared to contest an unprovoked Chinese attack on Taiwan or the islands of the South China Sea. But all of these scenarios except war on the Korean peninsula would be addressed chiefly with air and naval forces, not Marines. As for war against North Korea, the chief U.S. responses would involve its ground and air forces already in South Korea, air and naval forces in Japan and reinforcements from the United States. Other potential disputes with China should not be addressed militarily. <span style="font-size: 6pt;">We should follow another Nixon maxim, announced in his speech on Guam in 1969, that </span><span style="background: none repeat scroll 0% 0% gray;">the United States has no</span> long-term <span style="background: none repeat scroll 0% 0% gray;">interest in fighting land wars in Asia</span>. By <span style="background: none repeat scroll 0% 0% gray;">committing ourselves to</span> what would be primarily <span style="background: none repeat scroll 0% 0% gray;">a maritime</span> defense <span style="background: none repeat scroll 0% 0% gray;">strategy</span>, we <span style="background: none repeat scroll 0% 0% gray;">would deter China</span> from attacking our fundamental interests in the region without reinforcing its two-century old sense of encirclement and subjugation. If China some day caused military trouble in Indochina or Mongolia or other parts of mainland Asia, Washington and Tokyo could establish collective defense accords with other countries in the region to prevent any further encroachments. But these are matters where <span style="background: none repeat scroll 0% 0% gray;">hyper-vigilance now is unneeded, and</span> is <span style="background: none repeat scroll 0% 0% gray;">only</span> likely to <span style="background: none repeat scroll 0% 0% gray;">make things worse</span>. Taking some Marine combat forces home would greatly lessen the strains on Japan's smallest prefecture, now host to nearly 30,000 of the 45,000 American troops in Japan<span style="font-size: 6pt;">. For example, at the summit Clinton might agree to bring home one or two battalions out of the five typically there, including several thousand troops. Since there are only enough amphibious ships in Sasebo, Japan, for one battalion to be transported, this decision would hardly affect our rapid-response capabilities in the region. Indeed, Clinton and Hashimoto could even improve those capabilities by basing one or more additional amphibious ships in Japan. (The Marines' remaining 35 or so amphibious ships are at present based in the continental United States.) Japan too should take on new responsibilities. While reaffirming its one-China policy</span>, it should publicly and vocally reinforce the U.S. position that an unprovoked (or lightly provoked) Chinese attack on Taiwan would be grounds for extreme concern and joint action. <span style="font-size: 6pt;">In the military sphere, it should in the short term pass laws allowing it to provide substantial rear support to U.S. forces in times of crisis or war in the Asia-Pacific region. Those laws might be challenged in court, but Japanese politics today are healthy enough to handle whatever outcome this legal process might generate, including if necessary a national debate over modifying constitutional limits on Japan's military activities in wartime. </span>In the longer term, <span style="background: none repeat scroll 0% 0% gray;">Japan needs to become more of an equal military partner</span> to the United States. <span style="font-size: 6pt;">Areas for possible collaboration include expanded roles in peace operations, joint naval patrols with the 7th Fleet, and improved integration of communications systems with U.S. ships and planes to permit rapid sharing of targeting data in the event of war. </span>In these tense times in Asian politics, <span style="background: none repeat scroll 0% 0% gray;">restructuring the U.S.-Japan alliance would send a properly-mixed message to China</span> -- that the United States is generally uninterested in putting land forces up against China's borders, but that we and our allies will, if necessary, fight to defend our core interests in the region. And, by ensuring or even enhancing the Marines' ability to deploy quickly out of Okinawa, it would hardly give North Korea reason to cheer. Rather than simply forget this year's March madness in the Taiwan Straits, <span style="background: none repeat scroll 0% 0% gray;">we should get our </span>post-Cold War Asian <span style="background: none repeat scroll 0% 0% gray;">security relationships in shape to reduce the chance of another crisis</span>. 


