th a major strategic review. But there are risks to sticking with the status quo. <span style="background: none repeat scroll 0% 0% gray;">Tension in the U.S.-Japan alliance, revealed</span> so starkly <span style="background: none repeat scroll 0% 0% gray;">on Okinawa</span> last fall after U.S. servicemen raped a 12-year-old Japanese schoolgirl, <span style="background: none repeat scroll 0% 0% gray;">has been developing</span> ever since the end of the Cold War and could easily worsen. Japanese remain pro-American and in favor of the bilateral security relationship. But substantial and growing majorities believe that U.S. bases and military personnel in their country, essentially still at Cold War levels, should be reduced. True, the Japanese-American alliance weathered tough times in the past, surviving the Vietnam War and other major challenges. But in those days, the nearby Soviet threat helped the allies to say they were sorry and make up. Moreover, past crises often led to changes in the way the alliance worked -- and this one should too. At this point, <span style="background: none repeat scroll 0% 0% gray;">reinvigorating the alliance could best be accomplished by</span> changing the configuration of U.S. forces in Japan, including <span style="background: none repeat scroll 0% 0% gray;">a reduction in</span> the number of <span style="background: none repeat scroll 0% 0% gray;">Marine combat units on Okinawa</span>, while asking Japan to play a more forceful role in handling the fundamental future tasks of the alliance. The United States and Japan should distinguish between their vital interests and their important yet less-than-vital interests in Asia. Defense of the open oceans, sea lanes and existing U.S. allies -- Japan, South Korea, Australia, New Zealand, the Philippines and Thailand -- are the chief causes worth fighting for. The United States and Japan should also be prepared to contest an unprovoked Chinese attack on Taiwan or the islands of the 