here, including several thousand troops. Since there are only enough amphibious ships in Sasebo, Japan, for one battalion to be transported, this decision would hardly affect our rapid-response capabilities in the region. Indeed, Clinton and Hashimoto could even improve those capabilities by basing one or more additional amphibious ships in Japan. (The Marines' remaining 35 or so amphibious ships are at present based in the continental United States.) Japan too should take on new responsibilities. While reaffirming its one-China policy, it should publicly and vocally reinforce the U.S. position that an unprovoked (or lightly provoked) Chinese attack on Taiwan would be grounds for extreme concern and joint action. In the military sphere, it should in the short term pass laws allowing it to provide substantial rear support to U.S. forces in times of crisis or war in the Asia-Pacific region. Those laws might be challenged in court, but Japanese politics today are healthy enough to handle whatever outcome this legal process might generate, including if necessary a national debate over modifying constitutional limits on Japan's military activities in wartime. In the longer term, <span style="background: none repeat scroll 0% 0% gray;">Japan needs to become more of an equal military partner</span> to the United States. Areas for possible collaboration include expanded roles in peace operations, joint naval patrols with the 7th Fleet, and improved integration of communications systems with U.S. ships and planes to permit rapid sharing of targeting data in the event of war. In these tense times in Asian politics, <span style="background: none repeat scroll 0% 0% gray;">restructuring the U.S.-Japan alliance would send a properly-mixed message to China</span> -- that the United States is generally uninterested in putting land forces up against China's borders, but that we and our allies will, if necessary, fight to defend our core interests in the region. And, by ensuring or 