Readers may. Increased understanding of the transnational character of environmental problems has led toward a wonder why this Essay addresses international and global issues when NEPA applies only to action taken in the United States or by federal officials. The reason is that the United States is increasingly involved in global affairs, many having major environmental implications. In many of these situations, action by a U.S. agency automatically invokes NEPA. Although there has been controversy over the extent of NEPA's application to events overseas, there appears to be growing acceptance that NEPA means what it declares: the Act "promote[s] efforts which will prevent or eliminate damage to the environment and biosphere." n64 The number of transnational issues involving the United States and relevant to NEPA is large and growing. A complete list of examples would be long, but international trade and environment, global climate change, and effect of U.S. domestic policies on transnational issues would [*229] be prominent among them. World trends today that impact the future give NEPA a significance beyond that which it has had heretofore. The Act provides an agenda for addressing the transnational environmental issues of the future in which the United States is unavoidably involved convergence of national and international environmental law. n65 A growing body of positive international law and soft law (e.g., charters, declarations, resolutions) has been adopted or recognized by international organizations, especially organizations associated with the United Nations system. n66 International conventions (i.e., treaties) are the principal expressions of universal international environmental law. Under the Constitution of the United States, an international treaty, when ratified by the Senate, becomes analogous in important respects to a constitutional amendment. n67 Through this device, birds migrating between Canada and the United States were brought under federal protection, whereas previously all wildlife fell under the jurisdiction of the separate States. n68 International efforts, like efforts in the United States, to establish environmental protection as positive international law have been divided between declaring obligations of governments and rights of persons. The obligations of governments approach has been more inferential than direct. The United Nation's 1982 World Charter for Nature n69 would in principle impose obligations on governments but provides no way to enforce compliance. Although [*230] overwhelmingly endorsed by the U.N. General Assembly (the United States cast the only dissenting vote), few nations intended to honor its precepts. The occasion had as much to do with the internal politics of the General Assembly as with concern for the global environment. An indirect approach to national obligations has been through the internationally proposed requirement of environmental impact assessments modeled after NEPA. A resolution proposing a treaty to require signatory governments to prepare environmental assessments and to consult with other governments on potentially harmful proposals was introduced in the Senate on January 24, 1977 by Senator Claiborne Pell of Rhode Island. n70 The Resolution passed the Senate by voice vote on July 21, 1978, but no further action was taken by Congress. The international environmental assessment proposition was still alive in April 1979 when the concept was presented to the Governing Council of the United Nations Environment Programme. The U.N. Convention on Environmental Impact Assessment in a Transboundary Context n71 was signed on February 25, 1991 in Espoo, Finland. The United States signed the treaty but has not ratified it. As of early 1991 the treaty had not been ratified by a sufficient number of parties to enter into force. In 1989 at an International Congress in Rome, Amedeo Postiglione, a distinguished Italian jurist, proposed drafting a Universal Convention for the Environment as a Human Right that would have incorporated both the governmental obligations and individual rights approaches. The Convention, he declared, "should specify an individual's inalienable legal rights and establish an adequate level of information, participation, and actions necessary to maintain those rights and . . . should also define the main obligations of the individual States [and] . . . must identify the people responsible for promoting and protecting this human right." n72 In 1990 the Economic Commission for Europe proposed a Charter on Environmental Rights and Obligations. An initial version was published in [*231] the now-discontinued Brundtland Bulletin. n73 An acceptable version is still under consideration. In addition, Jacques Cousteau proposed an amendment to the U.N. Charter for transgenerational environmental equity. As of 1997 none of these efforts had succeeded, but they express an international concern which, while possibly premature, may become realizable in the future. The concept of global international environmental responsibility has been advanced by United Nations conferences on the environment and by resolutions adopted by the U.N. General Assembly. The Declaration of Principles adopted by the 1972 U.N. Conference at Stockholm asserted the fundamental human right to "an environment of a quality that permits a life of dignity and well-being." n74 It also asserted "a solemn responsibility to protect and improve the environment for present and future generations." n75 But the emphasis of the twenty-five principles declared at Stockholm was clearly on responsibilities rather than rights. The shorter Stockholm Declaration on the Human Environment was foremost a statement of duties and responsibilities. After setting forth the imperative to defend and improve the human environment, Paragraph 7 declared that: To achieve this environmental goal will demand the acceptance of responsibility by citizens and communities and by enterprises and institutions at every level, all sharing equitably in common efforts. Individuals in all walks of life as well as organizations in many fields, by their values and the sum of their actions, will shape the world environment of the future. Local and national governments will bear the greatest burden for large-scale environmental policy and action within their jurisdictions. International co-operation is also needed in order to raise resources to support the developing countries in carrying out their responsibilities in this field. A growing class of environmental problems, because they are regional or global in [*232] extent or because they affect the common international realm, will require extensive co-operation among nations and action by international organizations in the common interest. The Conference calls upon Governments and peoples to exert common efforts for the preservation and improvement of the human environment, for the benefit of all the people and for their posterity. n76 During the 1970s and 1980s, international commitment to environmental sustainability grew significantly. At Stockholm in 1972, less developed nations suspected that their economic development would be retarded by the environmental agenda proposed by the developed nations. In contrast, the 1992 U.N. Conference in Rio de Janeiro marked, at least rhetorically, a near-global consensus on the necessity for environmental protection as a condition for sustainable development. Principles of the Rio Declaration on Environment and Development adopted on June 14, 1992 declared that: States shall cooperate in a spirit of global partnership to conserve, protect and restore the health and integrity of the Earth's ecosystem. In view of the different contributions to global environmental degradation, States have common but differentiated responsibilities. The developed countries acknowledge the responsibility that they bear in the international pursuit of sustainable development in view 